I have been using Chair Gun for the past year and I love the app but it is no longer supported and also it does not support my model of scope. The makers of Chair Gun recommended Strelok and now I understand why. I recently bought Strelok Pro. For me the learning curve for Strelok was longer than Chair Gun but it does so much more and was worth the extra time I needed to learn it. Being able to set up multiple guns with different projectiles and scopes is AWESOME! Being able to see a copy of my actual reticle, with yardages marked for holdovers, holdunders etc is incredible. To me, this feature alone would be worth what the app cost but it does so much more. You could actually use the reticle function to visually compare differences in a first and second focal plane scope and also show someone how the holdover points are affected by the power of magnification being used on a second focal plane. Without a read "me file" or manual the app was a bit difficult for me to learn and if I were to rate only the app I would probably give it 4 stars because of this but then there is something called customer support that has to be considered. I bought the app for use with air guns and I was having difficulty getting it to calculate ballistic coefficients of less than 1000fps muzzle velocity. I sent Igor an email and he literally answered within 2 minutes. We exchanged several emails and each time his response time was unbelievably prompt. Does he sit by his computer saying send me a problem so I can fix it? Customer support was incredible. I still can't believe the level of support...for a 12 dollar app. I told him that I intended to rate the app 5 stars whether or not he could come up with a fix. He answered...I will fix. And fix is exactly what he did. It now works beautifully. With that kind of customer support I would rate him 10 stars if I could. Seriously folks...Spend the money. It will be some of the best money you have ever spent on shooting. It has given me not only an edge that I have never had but so much more of an understanding of what goes on after my projectile leaves the barrel. If you are only shooting tin cans at 25 yards it may not be that helpful but if you are shooting past 50 yards with an air gun (especially in the wind or past 200 with a powder burning rifle, in my opinion it will help you bring your shooting "A game" or perhaps even find it for the first time. The holidays are coming and this would make a great gift! This is a review from a guy who kept asking himself "Why should I buy an app when I have a free one that works just fine?" Spend the money and I believe you will find the answer just as I did.
replyContent: Thanks for such a great review. Words like this motivate me to move on and make my program even better!

In my experience, this app has been dead-on when you input your data for scope/reticle/bullet/rifle/yardage/ etc. My first introduction was the "free side" of the app several years ago. Works well, but it has acceptable data input limitations as it was "free". This lead me to purchase the "pro version". My only regret? I should have purchased it sooner and used it's outstanding parameters that can be used to get a first round "hit" where desired. However, the most important aspect of the app is the commitment of Igor Borisov, the app developer, to aid his client base to their specific needs. To wit: I have a Leupold 6.5-20X scope mounted on a .308. I had Leupold swap my mit-dot reticle for a TS29X-1 reticle. However, the pro version I was using did not have "wind curves" for this reticle. My decision was to ask Igor, if it were possible to get an upgrade to his app for the wind curves (which my buddies have on their apps in using other reticles). Igor answered my email within the same hour, said that he would write a program for this reticle and a couple of days later, I had it and am in business. In this day of "press 9, wait, press 3" answering menus, it's refreshing to have someone who is easy to contact, understands the client needs, doesn't need a committee to make a decision, and produces an update that performs as advertised. Again: BUY THE PRO VERSION. You will thank Igor for a well-designed app that truly does the job for long range hits. Sam

- Enter magnification the reticle was calibrated for. This is 24
 - Enter max. magnification as 50

content:
I love the app. It let's me run so much different data at the range and

This is the first ballistics app I have ever used, so not much to compare 
to, but I am really digging strelok pro. It has met all my expectations and 
then some. I use it for my Benjamin Marauder .25 and my hunting rifles. 
Haven't yet tried it with my. 22 and .308win. A chronograph is really 
something needed to get the most from this app. (That's the next purchase) 
Even without that tho, it has been way more accurate than anything else I 
have used, (range cards and drop charts etc.). Love the ability to switch 
between rifles and loads, range cards, and visual aid of hold over using 
the reticle. Big reason I got it was the reticle in my hunting rifle is a 
bdc type but 308win 180grn is not one of the load the bdc was designed for. 
Answer: strelok pro. Now I can find out my holds exactly at different 
magnification other than max @16x with a 150grn bullet. If I had to 
recommend anything to change it would be to make the reticle angle finding 
feature a "tap the screen" to lock in the angle rather than find the "ok" 
button. It can also be hard to read the red font at times on the angle 
reticle feature. Yellow seems a better choice.. Also what seems to be the 
biggest issue for folks myself included is finding the right reticle and 
/or magnification. I found similar versions of one my reticles (older Nikon 
buckmasters target dot 6-18x40), but not the right magnification, so I just 
ended up using the 1 moa dot. It works, I just don't have cross hairs. A 
way to upload your reticle via PDF or jpeg or something if you can't find 
it on the list would be a good feature. Otherwise, absolutely Loving 
strelok pro!
replyContent: Thank you for kind words! Locking slope angle - good idea, I will code it. And I will change font color to yellow

replyContent:
- select reticle with name "MilDot (USMC)"
- Tap the "Settings" button on the reticle screen and UNcheck the checkbox "This reticle is in the First Focal Plane (FFP)
- Enter Min. magnification as 4
- Enter magnification the reticle was calibrated for. This is usually 10 but check this value in the scope manual
 - Enter max. magnification as 16

When using a 20 MOA picatinny base on my Howa .308. Where do I add the value? Or where do I enter the information so the calculator knows that I am using a 20 MOA base. Thus the calculator can then determine the correct holdover. Because the scope height will be "x". But because of the base, the scope is not parallel to the barrel.
replyContent: There is the difference between  physical incline of the scope and incline line of view inside of the scope. First depends from base, second - not. It depends only from scope height above barrel and zero distance. If you entered correct scope height above barrel and zero distance, you already accounted your 20 MOA base.

replyContent: Factory ballistic data is true for factory rifle only. The same cartridge in your rifle will give you different muzzle speed and therefore different elevations. I think, calculated elevations is better to compare with your rifle real shot elevations. I suggest to mail me and we will try to resolve this issue together.

I recently upgraded to the strelok pro, and its spot on. You enter in all your data for your loads and scope and boom! you have a very accurate ballistic soultion. I have four of my rifles loaded into this app and its spot on for all of them, and two are rimfires which can be tricky to get a good soution for.  Start out by entering your rifle data which includes your scope data, zeroing conditions, and you cartridge data. Cartridge data includes gyroscopic stability factor, Bullet length, Bullet Diameter, Bullet Weight, ballistic coefficent, bullet speed, air temp, air temp sensitivity factor, and drag function. Then enter your barrel twist rate. Now enter your shooting distance, slope angle, wind speed, and direction. Push the calculate button and it gives you a total solution including windage/elevation, retained velocity, sound speed, flight time, click value, wind deflection, and spin drift. You can also view data in a seperate table, that can be emailed and printed. Its also bluetooth copatable for many bt capable weather stations. All in all its the best i've found and ive used just about all of them. Well worth the price.
